text:
Hey Justin, my personal suggestions are two-fold:

1. Don't talk about coronavirus. It's more than oversaturated right now. :sweat_smile: 
2. If you're in the B2B space: confirm the problems your customers are facing right now and offer super short and super clear advice on how to solve. If you're in B2C, I'm less familiar, but as a consumer right now all I'm looking for is content that is entertaining/interesting to consume and has nothing to do with C-19.

Don't talk about coronavirus. It's more than oversaturated right now.

If you're in the B2B space: confirm the problems your customers are facing right now and offer super short and super clear advice on how to solve. If you're in B2C, I'm less familiar, but as a consumer right now all I'm looking for is content that is entertaining/interesting to consume and has nothing to do with C-19.

text:
Some additional nuance -- I think it's ok to talk about COVID-19, but using it as your primary hook is 100% oversaturated and just...not very clever or tasteful.

Ex: We run a training program that we charge $$ for. We're currently donating a portion of the ticket price to a local organization that supports the homeless population in our city and is particularly under-resourced due to COVID-19. The primary message is still "Learn how to do this thing better", but the sub-text acknowledges the context we're currently living in.

text:
We're experiencing a problem where people are getting our automated emails (once they've signed up) straight into their spam.

Does anybody have any specific tips/tricks for automated campaigns breaking through spam?

Our monthly newsletter (Mailchimp) is fine but automation through Intercom isn't performing at all.

elements.text:
We're experiencing a problem where people are getting our automated emails (once they've signed up) straight into their spam.

Does anybody have any specific tips/tricks for automated campaigns breaking through spam?

Our monthly newsletter (Mailchimp) is fine but automation through Intercom isn't performing at all.

text:
It could be a couple things. It's possible that the email address you're using for the automation has been flagged enough times that you're going straight to spam. You could warm up a new email address to try out or use a different domain to send from.

There are also some spam checker tools out there you can use to test your email copy, etc. to see if there are any red flags. Here's one to try: <https://www.mailgenius.com/>

text: Never had this happen to me but I’ve been the person sending out those tax forms and I can see them just not wanting to wade into their own finances (maybe its laziness or an unwillingness to ruffle feathers internally). If you were to get audited, it would be YOU paying the price, not them. So I think you’re within reason to provide them with evidence. Maybe frame as being helpful? “Hey, I know you send a lot of these, Im seeing that my total payments number isnt right. I wouldnt want you to get in trouble with [IRS/your manager], can you double check…. etc etc”

text:
Janessa, you've previously mentioned "something to say" as a component of good writing. These are questions I like to ask to ensure I have something to say:

• Why would my audience be interested in this story?
• To what extent are they interested?
• What is the conflict of this story? 
• What’s kept it from being solved?
• Who are the people and industries that are affected?
• What are the consequences of inaction or the wrong solution?
• How will it be resolved?
• What’s the ultimate pay-off for my audience?
• What are the incremental pay-off points?

text:
Having a mismatch with a 1099 is going to trigger a red flag with the IRS automatically, but most likely they'll just send a letter asking for documentation to show the financials.

As long as you're providing an accurate amount, you won't get in trouble.

I recently had an issue with a 1099 misclassification (very long story) and based on the law, their penalties just for misclassifying me alone are likely around $60k  (FICA, unemployment, workers comp, interest, federal withholding, state withholding) and a misdemeanor charge for willful payroll tax evasion.

After that, I'm now always making sure my numbers absolutely match what I have on file rather than reporting blindly.
